ica’s selective self-exemption, Natsu Taylor Saito argues, undermines not only specific legal institutions and norms, but leads to a decreased effectiveness of the global rule of law. Meeting the Enemy is a pointed look at why the United States’ frequent-if selective-disregard of international law and institutions is met with such high levels of approval, or at least complacency, by the American public.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aExceptionalismxHistoryxUnited States. 0aExceptionalismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aInternational lawxPublic opinion. 0aInternational law. 0aManifest Destiny. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh  aAlthough.  aAmerican.  aConstitution.  aEnemy.  aMeeting.  aSince.  aStates.  aUnited.  aapproval.  acomplacency.  aconsistently.  adefined.  ademocracy.  adisregard.  adistanced.  aemphasized.  aensure.  aestablished.  afounding.  afreedom.  afrequent.  afrom.  ahigh.  ahome.  ahuman.  aimplement.  aimportance.  ainstitutions.  ainternational.  ainternationally.  aitself.  aleast.  alegal.  alevels.  alook.  amany.  amodel.  apointed.  apointing.  aprinciples.  aprotect.  aprotector.  apublic.  arights.  aselective.  asimultaneously.  asuch.  asupreme.  asystem.  athat.  athem.  athroughout.  awith.  aworld.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081479836240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814798362.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814786512423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814786512/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-